>

    <p>Japanese verb conjugation is the engine of the language — every sentence needs at least one verb, and that verb's form tells you the tense, politeness level, and mood. The good news? Japanese verbs do <strong>not change based on the subject</strong> (no "I eat / he eats / they eat" distinction), and there are only <strong>two irregular verbs</strong> in the entire language. According to the Japan Foundation, verb conjugation is the grammar topic that most directly determines your JLPT passing score.</p>

    <div style="margin: 2rem 0; padding: 1.2rem; background: linear-gradient(135deg, #fef2f2, #eff6ff); border-radius: 12px; border: 1px solid #e5e7eb; text-align: center;"><div style="font-size: 1.5rem; margin-bottom: 0.5rem;">🇯🇵</div><div style="font-weight: 700; color: #111827; font-size: 1rem;">Japanese Verb Conjugation</div><div style="color: #6b7280; font-size: 0.8rem; margin-top: 0.3rem;">Complete Learning Guide</div></div>


    <h2 id="three-groups">The Three Verb Groups Explained</h2>

    <div style="max-width:520px;margin:2rem auto;font-family:sans-serif">
      <div style="display:flex;gap:10px;flex-wrap:wrap;justify-content:center">
        <div style="flex:1;min-width:150px;border:2px solid #dc2626;border-radius:8px;padding:14px;text-align:center">
          <div style="background:#dc2626;color:#fff;padding:6px 10px;border-radius:4px;font-weight:bold;margin:-14px -14px 10px -14px;border-radius:6px 6px 0 0">Group 1 五段</div>
          <div style="font-size:0.85rem;color:#666">~75% of verbs</div>
          <div style="font-size:0.9rem;margin-top:6px">飲<strong>む</strong> · 書<strong>く</strong> · 話<strong>す</strong> · 買<strong>う</strong> · 待<strong>つ</strong></div>
        </div>
        <div style="flex:1;min-width:150px;border:2px solid #2563eb;border-radius:8px;padding:14px;text-align:center">
          <div style="background:#2563eb;color:#fff;padding:6px 10px;border-radius:4px;font-weight:bold;margin:-14px -14px 10px -14px;border-radius:6px 6px 0 0">Group 2 一段</div>
          <div style="font-size:0.85rem;color:#666">~20% of verbs</div>
          <div style="font-size:0.9rem;margin-top:6px">食べ<strong>る</strong> · 見<strong>る</strong> · 寝<strong>る</strong> · 起き<strong>る</strong></div>
        </div>
        <div style="flex:1;min-width:150px;border:2px solid #059669;border-radius:8px;padding:14px;text-align:center">
          <div style="background:#059669;color:#fff;padding:6px 10px;border-radius:4px;font-weight:bold;margin:-14px -14px 10px -14px;border-radius:6px 6px 0 0">Group 3 不規則</div>
          <div style="font-size:0.85rem;color:#666">Only 2 verbs</div>
          <div style="font-size:0.9rem;margin-top:6px"><strong>する</strong> (do) · <strong>来る</strong> (come)</div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>

    <p><strong>Group 1 (五段 godan / u-verbs):</strong> The largest group. The dictionary form always ends in an -u sound (む, く, す, う, つ, ぬ, ぶ, ぐ, る). Conjugation works by changing the final vowel. Examples: 飲<strong>む</strong> (nomu, drink), 書<strong>く</strong> (kaku, write), 話<strong>す</strong> (hanasu, speak), 待<strong>つ</strong> (matsu, wait).</p>
    <p><strong>Group 2 (一段 ichidan / ru-verbs):</strong> Verbs ending in -iru or -eru. Conjugation is simple: drop the final る and add the appropriate ending. Examples: 食べ<strong>る</strong> (taberu, eat), 見<strong>る</strong> (miru, see), 寝<strong>る</strong> (neru, sleep).</p>
    <p><strong>Group 3 (不規則 irregular):</strong> Only する (suru, to do) and 来る (kuru, to come). する is especially important because it combines with nouns to create hundreds of compound verbs: 勉強する (study), 運動する (exercise), 料理する (cook).</p>
    <p><strong>Tricky verbs:</strong> Some -iru/-eru verbs are actually Group 1: 帰る (kaeru, return), 走る (hashiru, run), 切る (kiru, cut), 入る (hairu, enter), 知る (shiru, know). These are common exceptions you must memorize.</p>

    <h2 id="polite-form">Polite Form (ます masu)</h2>
    <p>Polite form is used in most everyday situations and is the form most textbooks teach first:</p>

    <table style="width:100%;border-collapse:collapse;margin:1.5rem 0;font-size:0.95rem">
      <thead>
        <tr style="background:#2563eb;color:#fff">
          <th style="padding:10px 14px;text-align:left">Group</th>
          <th style="padding:10px 14px;text-align:left">Rule</th>
          <th style="padding:10px 14px;text-align:left">Dictionary → Polite</th>
        </tr>
      </thead>
      <tbody>
        <tr style="background:#eff6ff"><td style="padding:8px 14px"><strong>Group 1</strong></td><td style="padding:8px 14px">Change final -u to -imasu</td><td style="padding:8px 14px">飲<strong>む</strong> → 飲<strong>みます</strong> · 書<strong>く</strong> → 書<strong>きます</strong> · 話<strong>す</strong> → 話<strong>します</strong></td></tr>
        <tr style="background:#fff"><td style="padding:8px 14px"><strong>Group 2</strong></td><td style="padding:8px 14px">Drop -ru, add -masu</td><td style="padding:8px 14px">食べ<strong>る</strong> → 食べ<strong>ます</strong> · 見<strong>る</strong> → 見<strong>ます</strong></td></tr>
        <tr style="background:#eff6ff"><td style="padding:8px 14px"><strong>Group 3</strong></td><td style="padding:8px 14px">Memorize</td><td style="padding:8px 14px">する → <strong>します</strong> · 来る → <strong>来ます</strong> (きます)</td></tr>
      </tbody>
    </table>

    <p>For Group 1, the key is the vowel change: む→み, く→き, す→し, う→い, つ→ち, ぬ→に, ぶ→び, ぐ→ぎ, る→り. This pattern (changing to the -i row) applies to several conjugation forms, so learning it once pays off multiple times.</p>

    <h2 id="negative">Negative Form (ない nai)</h2>

    <table style="width:100%;border-collapse:collapse;margin:1.5rem 0;font-size:0.95rem">
      <thead>
        <tr style="background:#dc2626;color:#fff">
          <th style="padding:10px 14px;text-align:left">Group</th>
          <th style="padding:10px 14px;text-align:left">Rule</th>
          <th style="padding:10px 14px;text-align:left">Dictionary → Negative</th>
        </tr>
      </thead>
      <tbody>
        <tr style="background:#fef2f2"><td style="padding:8px 14px"><strong>Group 1</strong></td><td style="padding:8px 14px">Change final -u to -anai</td><td style="padding:8px 14px">飲<strong>む</strong> → 飲<strong>まない</strong> · 書<strong>く</strong> → 書<strong>かない</strong> · 話<strong>す</strong> → 話<strong>さない</strong></td></tr>
        <tr style="background:#fff"><td style="padding:8px 14px"><strong>Group 1 (う)</strong></td><td style="padding:8px 14px">Special: う → わない</td><td style="padding:8px 14px">買<strong>う</strong> → 買<strong>わない</strong> (not 買あない)</td></tr>
        <tr style="background:#fef2f2"><td style="padding:8px 14px"><strong>Group 2</strong></td><td style="padding:8px 14px">Drop -ru, add -nai</td><td style="padding:8px 14px">食べ<strong>る</strong> → 食べ<strong>ない</strong> · 見<strong>る</strong> → 見<strong>ない</strong></td></tr>
        <tr style="background:#fff"><td style="padding:8px 14px"><strong>Group 3</strong></td><td style="padding:8px 14px">Memorize</td><td style="padding:8px 14px">する → <strong>しない</strong> · 来る → <strong>来ない</strong> (こない)</td></tr>
        <tr style="background:#fef2f2"><td style="padding:8px 14px"><strong>ある (special)</strong></td><td style="padding:8px 14px">Irregular negative</td><td style="padding:8px 14px">ある → <strong>ない</strong> (not あらない)</td></tr>
      </tbody>
    </table>

    <p>Watch out for two exceptions: verbs ending in う change to わない (not あない), and ある becomes ない (the only verb besides する/来る with an irregular form).</p>

    <h2 id="past-tense">Past Tense (た ta / ました mashita)</h2>
    <p>Polite past tense is simple: change ます to ました. 食べます → 食べました. 飲みます → 飲みました.</p>
    <p>Casual past tense follows the same consonant change patterns as te-form (next section), but ends in た/だ instead of て/で:</p>

    <div style="max-width:500px;margin:2rem auto">
      <div style="margin-bottom:8px"><span style="display:inline-block;width:100px;font-weight:bold">む/ぬ/ぶ</span><div style="display:inline-block;background:#dc2626;color:#fff;padding:4px 12px;border-radius:4px;font-weight:bold">→ んだ</div><span style="margin-left:8px">飲む → 飲<strong>んだ</strong></span></div>
      <div style="margin-bottom:8px"><span style="display:inline-block;width:100px;font-weight:bold">く</span><div style="display:inline-block;background:#ef4444;color:#fff;padding:4px 12px;border-radius:4px;font-weight:bold">→ いた</div><span style="margin-left:8px">書く → 書<strong>いた</strong></span></div>
      <div style="margin-bottom:8px"><span style="display:inline-block;width:100px;font-weight:bold">ぐ</span><div style="display:inline-block;background:#f87171;color:#fff;padding:4px 12px;border-radius:4px;font-weight:bold">→ いだ</div><span style="margin-left:8px">泳ぐ → 泳<strong>いだ</strong></span></div>
      <div style="margin-bottom:8px"><span style="display:inline-block;width:100px;font-weight:bold">す</span><div style="display:inline-block;background:#fca5a5;color:#333;padding:4px 12px;border-radius:4px;font-weight:bold">→ した</div><span style="margin-left:8px">話す → 話<strong>した</strong></span></div>
      <div style="margin-bottom:8px"><span style="display:inline-block;width:100px;font-weight:bold">う/つ/る</span><div style="display:inline-block;background:#fecaca;color:#333;padding:4px 12px;border-radius:4px;font-weight:bold">→ った</div><span style="margin-left:8px">買う → 買<strong>った</strong></span></div>
    </div>

    <h2 id="te-form">Te-Form: The Swiss Army Knife of Japanese</h2>
    <p>Te-form is the most versatile conjugation — it unlocks dozens of grammar patterns. The rules follow the same consonant changes as past tense, but ending in て/で instead of た/だ:</p>

    <table style="width:100%;border-collapse:collapse;margin:1.5rem 0;font-size:0.95rem">
      <thead>
        <tr style="background:#7c3aed;color:#fff">
          <th style="padding:10px 14px;text-align:left">Ending</th>
          <th style="padding:10px 14px;text-align:left">Te-form</th>
          <th style="padding:10px 14px;text-align:left">Example</th>
        </tr>
      </thead>
      <tbody>
        <tr style="background:#f5f3ff"><td style="padding:8px 14px">む / ぬ / ぶ</td><td style="padding:8px 14px">→ んで</td><td style="padding:8px 14px">飲む → 飲<strong>んで</strong> · 死ぬ → 死<strong>んで</strong> · 遊ぶ → 遊<strong>んで</strong></td></tr>
        <tr style="background:#fff"><td style="padding:8px 14px">く</td><td style="padding:8px 14px">→ いて</td><td style="padding:8px 14px">書く → 書<strong>いて</strong> (exception: 行く → 行<strong>って</strong>)</td></tr>
        <tr style="background:#f5f3ff"><td style="padding:8px 14px">ぐ</td><td style="padding:8px 14px">→ いで</td><td style="padding:8px 14px">泳ぐ → 泳<strong>いで</strong></td></tr>
        <tr style="background:#fff"><td style="padding:8px 14px">す</td><td style="padding:8px 14px">→ して</td><td style="padding:8px 14px">話す → 話<strong>して</strong></td></tr>
        <tr style="background:#f5f3ff"><td style="padding:8px 14px">う / つ / る</td><td style="padding:8px 14px">→ って</td><td style="padding:8px 14px">買う → 買<strong>って</strong> · 待つ → 待<strong>って</strong> · 帰る → 帰<strong>って</strong></td></tr>
        <tr style="background:#fff"><td style="padding:8px 14px">Group 2 (-ru)</td><td style="padding:8px 14px">→ drop る, add て</td><td style="padding:8px 14px">食べる → 食べ<strong>て</strong> · 見る → 見<strong>て</strong></td></tr>
        <tr style="background:#f5f3ff"><td style="padding:8px 14px">Group 3</td><td style="padding:8px 14px">Memorize</td><td style="padding:8px 14px">する → <strong>して</strong> · 来る → <strong>来て</strong> (きて)</td></tr>
      </tbody>
    </table>

    <p><strong>What te-form enables:</strong></p>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>Requests:</strong> 食べて<strong>ください</strong> = Please eat</li>
      <li><strong>Progressive:</strong> 食べて<strong>いる</strong> = Is eating (right now)</li>
      <li><strong>Permission:</strong> 食べて<strong>もいい</strong> = May I eat?</li>
      <li><strong>Prohibition:</strong> 食べて<strong>はいけない</strong> = Must not eat</li>
      <li><strong>Sequence:</strong> 食べて飲んで寝る = Eat, drink, and sleep</li>
    </ul>

    <h2 id="potential">Potential Form: Expressing Ability</h2>
    <p>Potential form expresses "can do" something:</p>

    <table style="width:100%;border-collapse:collapse;margin:1.5rem 0;font-size:0.95rem">
      <thead>
        <tr style="background:#059669;color:#fff">
          <th style="padding:10px 14px;text-align:left">Group</th>
          <th style="padding:10px 14px;text-align:left">Rule</th>
          <th style="padding:10px 14px;text-align:left">Example</th>
        </tr>
      </thead>
      <tbody>
        <tr style="background:#ecfdf5"><td style="padding:8px 14px"><strong>Group 1</strong></td><td style="padding:8px 14px">Change -u to -eru</td><td style="padding:8px 14px">飲む → 飲<strong>める</strong> (can drink) · 書く → 書<strong>ける</strong> (can write)</td></tr>
        <tr style="background:#fff"><td style="padding:8px 14px"><strong>Group 2</strong></td><td style="padding:8px 14px">Drop -ru, add -rareru</td><td style="padding:8px 14px">食べる → 食べ<strong>られる</strong> (can eat) · 見る → 見<strong>られる</strong> (can see)</td></tr>
        <tr style="background:#ecfdf5"><td style="padding:8px 14px"><strong>Group 3</strong></td><td style="padding:8px 14px">Memorize</td><td style="padding:8px 14px">する → <strong>できる</strong> · 来る → <strong>来られる</strong> (こられる)</td></tr>
      </tbody>
    </table>

    <p><strong>Note:</strong> In casual speech, Group 2 potential form often drops the ら: 食べられる → 食べれる (called "ra-nuki"). While technically non-standard, this is extremely common among younger speakers.</p>

    <h2 id="conjugation-chart">Complete Conjugation Chart</h2>
    <p>Here is a summary of all major forms for the three example verbs:</p>

    <table style="width:100%;border-collapse:collapse;margin:1.5rem 0;font-size:0.9rem">
      <thead>
        <tr style="background:#374151;color:#fff">
          <th style="padding:8px 12px;text-align:left">Form</th>
          <th style="padding:8px 12px;text-align:left">飲む (G1)</th>
          <th style="padding:8px 12px;text-align:left">食べる (G2)</th>
          <th style="padding:8px 12px;text-align:left">する (G3)</th>
        </tr>
      </thead>
      <tbody>
        <tr style="background:#f9fafb"><td style="padding:6px 12px"><strong>Dictionary</strong></td><td style="padding:6px 12px">飲む</td><td style="padding:6px 12px">食べる</td><td style="padding:6px 12px">する</td></tr>
        <tr style="background:#fff"><td style="padding:6px 12px"><strong>Polite</strong></td><td style="padding:6px 12px">飲みます</td><td style="padding:6px 12px">食べます</td><td style="padding:6px 12px">します</td></tr>
        <tr style="background:#f9fafb"><td style="padding:6px 12px"><strong>Negative</strong></td><td style="padding:6px 12px">飲まない</td><td style="padding:6px 12px">食べない</td><td style="padding:6px 12px">しない</td></tr>
        <tr style="background:#fff"><td style="padding:6px 12px"><strong>Past</strong></td><td style="padding:6px 12px">飲んだ</td><td style="padding:6px 12px">食べた</td><td style="padding:6px 12px">した</td></tr>
        <tr style="background:#f9fafb"><td style="padding:6px 12px"><strong>Te-form</strong></td><td style="padding:6px 12px">飲んで</td><td style="padding:6px 12px">食べて</td><td style="padding:6px 12px">して</td></tr>
        <tr style="background:#fff"><td style="padding:6px 12px"><strong>Potential</strong></td><td style="padding:6px 12px">飲める</td><td style="padding:6px 12px">食べられる</td><td style="padding:6px 12px">できる</td></tr>
        <tr style="background:#f9fafb"><td style="padding:6px 12px"><strong>Volitional</strong></td><td style="padding:6px 12px">飲もう</td><td style="padding:6px 12px">食べよう</td><td style="padding:6px 12px">しよう</td></tr>
      </tbody>
    </table>

